## Folder Structure

```
portfolio/
├── index.html                          # Main page — all sections
├── style.css                           # Full stylesheet (design system, layout, animations)
├── script.js                           # All interactivity (vanilla JS, no dependencies)
├── README.md                           # This file
├── favicon.ico                         # Site favicon
└── assets/
    ├── images/
    │   ├── profile.jpg                 # Hero profile photo (circular, glassmorphism frame)
    │   ├── project1.png                # Project screenshot — JavaScript CRUD System
    │   ├── project2.png                # Project screenshot — UI/UX Prototype Design
    │   └── project3.png                # Project screenshot — Academic Research Projects
    ├── documents/
    │   └── Lyl-Valerie-Busca-CV.pdf    # Downloadable CV (linked from the "Download CV" button)
    └── icons/                          # Reserved for any additional custom icon assets
```

> **Note on placeholder assets:** `project1.png`, `project2.png`, `project3.png`, and the CV PDF were generated as clean placeholders so the site is complete and deployable out of the box. Swap them for real project screenshots and Valerie's actual CV file (keeping the same filenames, or updating the paths in `index.html`) whenever they're ready.

---

## Installation

No build step, no package manager, no dependencies to install.

1. Download or clone this `portfolio/` folder.
2. Open `index.html` directly in a browser, **or** serve it locally for the best experience (some browsers restrict local file access for certain features):

   ```bash
   # Python 3
   cd portfolio
   python3 -m http.server 8000
   # then visit http://localhost:8000
   ```

   ```bash
   # Node.js (if installed)
   npx serve portfolio
   ```

---

## Customization

- **Colors:** all palette colors are defined once as CSS custom properties at the top of `style.css` under `:root`. Change `--primary`, `--secondary`, `--accent`, `--bg`, and `--dark` to restyle the entire site instantly.
- **Fonts:** loaded via Google Fonts in `index.html` (`Poppins` for display/headings, `Inter` for body text). Swap the `<link>` tag and the `--font-display` / `--font-body` variables in `style.css` to change fonts.
- **Content:** all text content lives directly in `index.html`, organized by section with clear comments (`<!-- HERO SECTION -->`, `<!-- ABOUT SECTION -->`, etc.).
- **Profile photo:** replace `assets/images/profile.jpg` with a new image of the same aspect ratio (square, ideally 800×800px or larger) to update the Hero photo — no code changes needed.
- **Projects:** duplicate a `.project-card` block in the Projects section and update the image, title, description, tech badges, and links to add more projects.
- **Skills:** each skill bar's fill percentage is controlled by the `data-width` attribute on `.skill-fill` and `data-target` on `.skill-percent` — update both to the same number to change a skill's displayed level.
- **Dark mode default:** the site respects the visitor's OS-level dark/light preference on first visit, then remembers their manual toggle choice via `localStorage`.

---

## GitHub Pages Deployment

1. Create a new GitHub repository (e.g. `portfolio`).
2. Push the entire contents of this `portfolio/` folder to the repository's root (or to a `docs/` folder if you prefer).
3. In the repository, go to **Settings → Pages**.
4. Under **Build and deployment → Source**, select **Deploy from a branch**.
5. Choose the branch (usually `main`) and the root folder (`/` or `/docs`), then save.
6. GitHub will publish the site at:
   ```
   https://<your-username>.github.io/<repository-name>/
   ```
7. Update the `og:url` and `canonical` meta tags in `index.html` with your actual published URL for correct link previews and SEO.

No additional configuration, build step, or `.nojekyll` file is required since this is a static HTML/CSS/JS site.

